[{"id":"/sicp/1.1.6","tag":"TITLE","body":"1.1.6  \n    Conditional Expressions and Predicates"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p1","child":[{"body":"\n    The expressive power of the class of\n    \n\tprocedures\n      \n    that we can define at this point is very limited, because we have no way to\n    make tests and to perform different operations depending on the result of a\n    test.\n    \n        For instance, we cannot define a procedure that computes the \n        \n        absolute\n        value of a number by testing whether the number is positive, negative,\n        or zero and taking different actions in the different cases according\n        to the rule\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\n      \\[\\begin{array}{lll}\n          |x| & = & \\left\\{ \\begin{array}{rl}\n          x   & \\text{if $x>0$} \\\\\n          0   & \\text{if $x=0$} \\\\\n          -x  & \\text{if $x<0$}\n          \\end{array}\n          \\right.\n      \\end{array}\\]\n        ","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"\n        This construct is called a\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"case analysis","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":", and\n        there is a special form in Lisp for notating such a case\n        analysis.  It is called \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" (which stands for\n        \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"conditional","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"), and it is used as follows:\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":1,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAjAZxAA8BKNEcgYwHtjtzMA+BiAAMjBs1YSJmTAF5BI4eMlTMAHnmjMAWjGM9GSrXI6ArHqA","body":"(define (abs x)\n  (cond ((> x 0) x)\n        ((= x 0) 0)\n        ((< x 0) (- x)))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":2,"eval":false,"body":"(abs (- 5))"},{"body":"\n        The general form of a conditional expression is\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(cond ($\\langle p_1 \\rangle $ $\\langle e_1 \\rangle$)\n      ($\\langle p_2 \\rangle $ $\\langle e_2 \\rangle$)\n      $\\vdots$\n      ($\\langle p_n \\rangle $ $\\langle e_n \\rangle$))\n          "},{"body":"\n        consisting of the symbol ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" followed by\n        \n        parenthesized pairs of expressions\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"("},{"body":"$\\langle p\\ e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":")"},{"body":"\n        called \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"clauses","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":". The first expression in each pair is a \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"predicate","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"—that is, an expression whose value is\n\tinterpreted as either true or false.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-1","body":"1","href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-1"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p2","child":[{"body":"\n        Conditional expressions are\n        \n\tevaluated as follows.  The predicate\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p_1 \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" is evaluated first.\n\tIf its value is false, then\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p_2 \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" is evaluated.  \n        If ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p_2 \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s \n        value is also false, then\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p_3 \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" is evaluated.  \n        This process continues until a predicate is\n        found whose value is true, in which case the interpreter returns the\n        value of the corresponding \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"consequent expression","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" of the\n        clause as the value of the conditional expression.  If none of the\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s\n\tis found to be true, the value of the ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":"\n\tis undefined.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p3","child":[{"body":"\n        The word\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"predicate","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" is used for procedures that return true\n        or false, as well as for expressions that evaluate to true or false.\n        The absolute-value procedure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"abs"},{"body":" makes use of the \n        \n        primitive predicates ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":">"},{"body":", \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"<"},{"body":", and \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"="},{"body":".","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-2","body":"2","href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-2"},{"body":" These take two numbers as arguments and\n\ttest whether the first number is, respectively, greater than, less than,\n\tor equal to the second number, returning true or false accordingly.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p4","child":[{"body":"\n        Another way to write the absolute-value procedure is\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":3,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAjAZxAA8BKNEcgYwHtjtzMAeBiAAMjcgFoGjZq1aZcAGxpkmUjJVriQAVilA","body":"(define (abs x)\n  (cond ((< x 0) (- x))\n    (else x))) "},{"body":"\n        which could be expressed in English as \n        \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"If ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$x$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" is less than zero\n        return ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$- x$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"; otherwise return \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$x$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Else"},{"body":" is a special symbol that can be used\n\tin place of the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" in the\n\tfinal clause of a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":".  \n        This causes the ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" to return as its value \n        the value of the corresponding\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        whenever all previous clauses have been bypassed. In fact, any\n\texpression that always evaluates to a true value could be used as the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" here.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p5","child":[{"body":"\n        Here is yet another way to write the absolute-value procedure:\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":4,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAjAZxAA8BKNEcw-cgHgZAAZnWrTAFoGAwU2ZZqdESACsjRkA","body":"(define (abs x)\n  (if (< x 0)\n    (- x)\n    x)) "},{"body":"\n        This uses the\n        \n\tspecial form ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":", a restricted \n        type of conditional that can be used when there are precisely \n        \n        two cases in the case\n        analysis.  The general form of an ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":"\n\texpression is\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(if $\\langle \\textit{predicate} \\rangle$ $\\langle \\textit{consequent}\\rangle$ $\\langle \\textit{alternative}\\rangle$)\n          "},{"body":"\n        To\n        \n\tevaluate an ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":" expression, \n        the interpreter starts by evaluating the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{predicate}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        part of the expression.  \n        If the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{predicate}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        evaluates to a true value, the interpreter then evaluates the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{consequent}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        and returns its value.  Otherwise it evaluates the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{alternative}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        and returns its value.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-3","body":"3","href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-3"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p6","child":[{"body":"\n        In addition to primitive predicates such as\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"<"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"="},{"body":", and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":">"},{"body":",\n\tthere are logical composition operations, which enable us to construct\n\tcompound predicates.  The three most frequently used are these:\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(and"},{"body":"$\\langle e_1\\rangle \\ldots \\langle e_n \\rangle$ \t    ","tag":"LATEX"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":")"},{"tag":"BR"},{"body":"\n            The interpreter evaluates the expressions\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" one at a time, \n            in left-to-right order.  If any\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" evaluates to false, \n            the value of the ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"and"},{"body":" expression is\n\t    false, and the rest of the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s \n            are not evaluated. If all\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s\n\t    evaluate to true values, the value of the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"and"},{"body":"\n            expression is the value of the last one.\n          ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(or"},{"body":"$\\langle e_1 \\rangle\\ldots \\langle e_n \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":")"},{"tag":"BR"},{"body":"\n            The interpreter evaluates the expressions \n            ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" one at a time, in\n\t    left-to-right order.  If any\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"\n\t    evaluates to a true value, that value is returned as the value of the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"or"},{"body":" expression, and the rest of the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s are not\n\t    evaluated. If all\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"'s\n\t    evaluate to false, the value of the\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"or"},{"body":" expression is false.\n          ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(not"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":") \t    "},{"tag":"BR"},{"body":"\n            The value of a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"not"},{"body":" expression is true\n            when the expression ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n            evaluates to false, and false otherwise.\n          ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n        Notice that ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"and"},{"body":" and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"or"},{"body":" are special forms, not procedures,\n        because the subexpressions are not necessarily all evaluated.\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Not"},{"body":" is an ordinary procedure.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p7","child":[{"body":"\n        As an example of how these are used, the condition that a \n        number ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$x$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" be in the range\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$5 < x < 10$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" may be expressed as\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":5,"eval":false,"body":"(and (> x 5) (< x 10))"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p8","child":[{"body":"\n    As another example, we can\n    \n\tdefine\n      \n    a predicate to test whether one number is \n    \n    greater than or equal to another as    \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":6,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwD4BeEADxAE8BKNEcgewCdyK7GnyNesyYss1EAHYQAFiZA","body":"(define (>= x y)\n  (or (> x y) (= x y))) "},{"body":"\n    or alternatively as\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":7,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwD4BeEADxAE8BKNEc4gewBdyAeOxkyEZKNAOwgALEyA","body":"(define (>= x y)\n  (not (< x y))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 1.1","id":"#ex-1.1","child":[{"body":"\n    Below is a sequence of\n    \n\texpressions.\n      \n    What is the result printed by the interpreter in response to each\n    \n        expression?\n      \n    Assume that the sequence is to be evaluated in the order\n    in which it is presented.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":8,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUG+AGIA","body":"10 "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":9,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAahAVhAGYQAWASiA","body":"(+ 5 3 4) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":10,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAWhATgQEog","body":"(- 9 1) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":11,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAehCkATAJRA","body":"(/ 6 2) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":12,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAahJgVCAEwgAsAlHgLRkgrnlA","body":"(+ (* 2 4) (- 4 6)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":13,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASiA","body":"(define a 3) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":14,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGmoA","body":"(define b (+ a 1)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":15,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurTy1pgBUXZjyA","body":"(+ a b (* a b)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":16,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurAXi7MaQA","body":"(= a b) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":17,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurQ-NuWLY2APhCtyNNgB4JbAFRdmPOiAlp1UoA","body":"(if (and (> b a) (< b (* a b)))\n  b\n  a) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":18,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurAYwD2xbG0wBeLgBYaIFHRALFmcSFbS2nFCADsFHmkVLcAGwDOZAEwBWHkA","body":"(cond ((= a 4) 6)\n      ((= b 4) (+ 6 7 a))\n      (else 25)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":19,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurTgJjaF8bAHwhW5GhIo8gA","body":"(+ 2 (if (> b a) b a)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":20,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMQBmASgxwJLICMRMBqChGurAKjYBjAPbFsbTAD4uzGhTohFSpZkwAeGXNlpluzLgA2AZzIBaeDx2KOXCzSA","body":"(* (cond ((> a b) a)\n         ((< a b) b)\n         (else -1))\n   (+ a 1)) "}],"solution":[{"body":"\n      Solution provided by GitHub user Emekk\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"10","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"12","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"8","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"3","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"6","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"no value","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"no value","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"19","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"false","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"4","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"16","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"6","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"16","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n\t  Note that the definitions ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(define a 3)"},{"body":" and\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(define b (+ a 1))"},{"body":" do not produce a value.\n\t","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 1.2","id":"#ex-1.2","child":[{"body":"\n    Translate the following expression into \n    \n        prefix form\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\n      $\\begin{array}{l}\n      \\quad~~\\dfrac{5+4+\\left(2-\\left(3-(6+\\frac{4}{5})\\right)\\right)}{3 (6-2) (2-7)}\n      \\end{array}$\n    ","tag":"LATEX"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":21,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 1.3","id":"#ex-1.3","child":[{"body":"\n        Define a procedure\n      \n    that takes three numbers as arguments and returns\n    the sum of the squares of the two larger numbers.\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":22,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGcBHAVwEMAnMgDwEpyAqEZ711jHARJlM+biACeIAF78Q8zABtcAF3KUAtnUXKKazITGYAfOInsDR01NkzJFw+VM9b03nznyvmALTkA1OTU9Ey8QbSMZObhIWSyFsGRIBRaOrh6HvxYYgAsIADsIABMrEA","body":"(define (f x y z)\n   (let ((smallest (if (> x y) (if (> y z) z y) (if (> x z) z x))))\n      (- (+ (square x) (square y) (square z)) (square smallest)))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 1.4","id":"#ex-1.4","child":[{"body":"\n\tObserve that our model of evaluation allows for\n\t\n\tcombinations whose\n\toperators are compound expressions.  Use this observation to describe\n\tthe behavior of the following procedure:\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":23,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMBaABwBsBXAZyooCMW2QKQ2BKNCHKZC+cgD5eIAAx8QAahBU5PfnyA","body":"(define (a-plus-abs-b a b)\n  ((if (> b 0) + -) a b)) "}],"solution":[{"body":"\n\t  According to section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.1.5","href":"/sicp/1.1.5"},{"body":", evaluation\n\t  of an application proceeds as follows:\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"Evaluate the subexpressions of the application.\n\t    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"Evaluate the return expression of the result of\n\t    the function expression with each\n\t    parameter replaced by the corresponding result of the respective\n\t    argument expression.\n            ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n\t  Thus the evaluation of the application \n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"a_plus_abs_b(5, -4)"},{"body":"\n\t  (1) evaluates ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"a_plus_abs_b"},{"body":",\n\t  resulting in the function given above, and the arguments are\n\t  already values. So we need to evaluate (2) the return expression\n\t  of the function, with the parameters replaced by the arguments, thus:\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(-4 >= 0 ? plus : minus)(5, -4)"},{"body":".\n\t  With the same rules, we need to (1) evaluate the function expression,\n\t  which in this case is the conditional expression\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"-4 >= 0 ? plus : minus"},{"body":". Since\n\t  the predicate evaluates to false, the function expression\n\t  evaluates to ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"minus"},{"body":". The arguments,\n\t  again (1) are already values. Thus we end up evaluating (2) the body of\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"minus"},{"body":" with the parameters\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"a"},{"body":" and\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"b"},{"body":" replaced by 5 and -4,\n\t  respectively, resulting in\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"5 - (-4)"},{"body":", which will finally\n\t  evaluate to 9.\n\t","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 1.5","id":"#ex-1.5","child":[{"body":"\n    Ben Bitdiddle has invented a test to determine whether the interpreter\n    he is faced with is using\n    \n    applicative-order evaluation or normal-order\n    evaluation. He \n    \n\tdefines the following two procedures:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":24,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwAcBKc6qjHAkszAF1wGdWQAPEAT3ohyhfOQC8vEAAYhwmWnkCqVIA","body":"(define (p) (p))\n\n(define (test x y)\n  (if (= x 0)\n    0\n    y)) "},{"body":"\n      Then he evaluates the\n      expression","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":25,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=1&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiCMA6JA2AUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwAcBKc6qjHAkszAF1wGdWQAPEAT3ohyhfOQC8vEAAYhwmWnkCq9LOy4zaKoA","body":"(test 0 (p)) "},{"body":"\n      What behavior will Ben observe with an interpreter that uses\n      applicative-order evaluation?  What behavior will he observe with an\n      interpreter that uses normal-order evaluation?  Explain your answer.\n      \n      (Assume that the evaluation rule for \n      \n          the special form ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":"\n      is the same whether the interpreter is using normal or applicative order:\n      The predicate expression is evaluated first, and the result determines\n      whether to evaluate the consequent or the alternative expression.)\n      ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"\"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"Interpreted as either\n         \n\ttrue or false","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"\n        means this: In Scheme, there are two distinguished values that are\n        denoted by the constants \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#t"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#f"},{"body":".  \n        When the interpreter checks a predicate's value, it interprets \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#f"},{"body":" as false.  Any other value\n        is treated as true.  (Thus, providing ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#t"},{"body":"\n\tis logically unnecessary, but it is convenient.)  In this book we will\n\tuse names ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"true"},{"body":" and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"false"},{"body":", \n        which are associated with the values ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#t"},{"body":" and \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"#f"},{"body":" respectively.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-link-2","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Abs"},{"body":" also uses\n        \n        the \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"minus","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" operator ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"-"},{"body":", \n        which, when used with a single\n        operand, as in ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(- x)"},{"body":", \n        indicates negation.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-3","count":3,"href":"/sicp/1.1.6#footnote-link-3","child":[{"body":"A minor \n        difference\n        \n\tbetween ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":" and \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" is that the\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        part of each ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" \n        clause may be a sequence of expressions.\n        If the corresponding ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle p \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        is found to be true, \n        the expressions \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle e \\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" \n        are evaluated in sequence and the value of the final\n        expression in the sequence is returned as the value of the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":".\n        In an ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"if"},{"body":" expression, however, \n        the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{consequent}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" and\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$\\langle \\textit{alternative}\\rangle$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" must\n\tbe single expressions.","tag":"#text"}]}]